Legal plays:\
	In order for a card placed on another to be considered valid, it must be of equal or greater rank than the card it is placed on (except in the case of the 7 card being played).\
	Certain cards have special abilities. These are:\
		A: The highest card. Also allows the player to nominate another player to play next. This nomination can be the player himself, meaning he/she has another turn.\
		2: Playable on anything. Also known as the \'93reset card\'94. Anything can be played on a 2 and a 2 can be played on anything.\
		5: Glass card. When this card is played, the next player has to play on the card that sits below the 5 (or below a stack of 5\'92s). This card can also be played on any other card.\
		7: Reverse card. The next player (and only the next player) has to play a rank equal to or lower than a 7.\
		8: Skip card. The next player loses their turn. This is stackable, i.e. playing two 8\'92s skips the next 2 players.\
		10: Burn card. The discard pile is removed, and the player that played the 10 card gets to play again. This card can NOT be played on any card and must be of higher rank than the previous card.\
		Q: Direction switch card. The direction of play is reversed. Stacking Q cards allows for the direction of play to change accordingly, i.e. playing two Q\'92s has the same effect as playing none since direction is 			reversed twice.\
